<subSubSection pageId="24" pageNumber="132" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="24.[189,310,330,356]" box="[189,310,330,356]" pageId="24" pageNumber="132">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,310,330,356]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="24" pageNumber="132" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,310,330,356]" pageId="24" pageNumber="132">Diagnosis</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="24.[187,1399,377,509]" pageId="24" pageNumber="132">
Species with complete and not internally carinate notauli and smooth mesoscutum, similar to 
<emphasis box="[1256,1397,377,403]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="132">
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Dalman" baseAuthorityYear="1823" box="[1256,1393,377,403]" class="Insecta" family="Figitidae" genus="Aegilips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="24" pageNumber="132" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nitidulus">A.nitidulus</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
However, most of the mesopleural surface is completely wrinkled, a character exclusive of this species (other Palaeartic species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Haliday" authorityYear="1835" box="[524,620,447,473]" class="Insecta" family="Figitidae" genus="Aegilips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="24" pageNumber="132" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[524,620,447,473]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="132">Aegilips</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
present some antero-ventral carinae in the mesopleuron but they never reach central mesopleuron).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
